english:
  title: 'A Rooster''s Virtue: An Inscription with Preface'
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I once kept a rooster in my house. I would call it with leftover rice, and soon this became its nature—whenever I sat down to eat, it would come clucking softly to my side, waiting to be fed. When I read, the bird would stand or crouch, sometimes lifting one foot to linger beneath my desk, as if understanding the words I studied. When I wrote, it would peck at the inkstone and tilt its head, watching with keen eyes, as if comprehending the characters themselves. When I rose from long sitting, tired and weary, to walk among the gardens and courtyards, the rooster would lower its wings and keep its feet aligned, following my steps just as a student follows a master.

    Now, the rooster is but livestock, and its closeness to man is its nature. Yet that it has come to love us—this is because we have moved its heart. Among all creatures, none possesses the spirit of man; therefore we can tame the great tigers, rhinoceroses, and elephants, as well as the small birds, fish, and insects. But these wild creatures, though we may force them to obey, are difficult to move through kindness alone. The rooster, by its nature, needs only guidance to follow willingly.

    The ancients spoke of the rooster's five virtues, yet they did not mention its love for man. Today I declare that the rooster's love for us is itself a form of humanity. Is this not so? Thus I compose this inscription to mark this truth:

    How little difference between a rooster's nature and our own—
    When moved, it responds at once.
    We are of the same kind, after all.
    Does the rooster show me humanity,
    Or do I show it humanity?

    O rooster, may you never abandon the thread that binds us together.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''five virtues'' of the rooster traditionally refer to its martial prowess, courage, protective nature, generosity in sharing food, and punctuality. The author here suggests a sixth virtue: the capacity to love humans.'
    - The rooster serves as a mirror for human virtue in this work, reflecting Neo-Confucian ideas about the reciprocal nature of benevolence (仁, ren/인) and the spiritual continuity between humans and animals.
